## Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the StrategyOS Demo project.

### Changes Made

**1. Installed Dependencies**
- Added `@vercel/analytics` package (v2.0.1) to dependencies
- Updated package-lock.json with the new dependency tree

**2. Updated Root Layout (app/layout.tsx)**
- Imported the `Analytics` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
- Added the `<Analytics />` component to the body of the root layout, placed after `{children}` as recommended by Vercel's Next.js App Router documentation

**3. Configuration Files**
- tsconfig.json was automatically updated by Next.js build process to include `.next/dev/types/**/*.ts` in the include paths (standard Next.js behavior)

### Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Web Analytics quickstart guide (fetched May 7, 2026), I implemented the Analytics component according to the Next.js App Router pattern:

```typescript
import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next"

// Inside the RootLayout component's return:
<body>
  {children}
  <Analytics />
</body>
```

This integration provides:
- Automatic page view tracking for all routes
- Seamless integration with Next.js App Router
- Zero-configuration setup (works out of the box once deployed to Vercel)

### Verification

- ✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
- ✅ TypeScript compilation passed
- ✅ All dependencies installed correctly
- ✅ Project structure preserved with minimal, targeted changes

### Next Steps

To enable Web Analytics in production:
1. Deploy the project to Vercel
2. Navigate to your project's Analytics tab in the Vercel dashboard
3. Click "Enable" to activate Web Analytics
4. After deployment, verify functionality by checking for Fetch/XHR requests to `/<unique-path>/view` in the browser's Network tab

The Analytics component will automatically start tracking page views once the project is deployed to Vercel and Analytics is enabled in the dashboard.
